description.narrative:
The overall objectives of the intervention are to generate new knowledge,  strengthen research capacity and promote transdisciplinary research to find solutions for ocean sustainability on the African Continent.
The specific objectives of this program are:
to administer CRA grants in Somalia, Kenya, Mozambique and Madagascar;
to provide technical assistance to selected institutions to support the design, implementation and monitoring of innovative approaches and interventions for the CRA project;
to manage capacity building or networking activities to support effective delivery of the CRA programs;
to follow up on projects and reporting;
to document, process and develop a learning model capable of facilitating continuous learning, increased impact and sustainability of the funded CRA projects.

The general objective of the civic space component is to protect and widen the democratic space and create necessary conditions for DRC to consolidate democracy through the full respect and effective exercise of all human rights as a base for stability and peace in the country.
The specific objectives are the following five:
1. The National Human Rights Institutions capacities (Human Rights Commission and Ministry of Human Rights) are strengthened at central and provincial level delivering more effectively their mandate of protection and promotion of human rights, with special regards to those directly related to the protection and promotion of civic space;
2. Violations of human rights and fundamental freedoms in the context of the democratic space are duly monitored and reported and when possible prevented;
3. The capacities of various components of civil society (CSO, NGO, media and journalists, civic activist) as well as those of state actors are strengthened so that they can effectively play their role in support of full knowledge, respect and effective exercise of political rights and fundamental freedoms;
4. HRD, victims and witnesses of HRV are protected from human rights violation (including those of protection of physical integrity, life, property, etc.) and can exercise their political rights and fundamental freedom without fear, etc.;
5. The access to justice and reparation for the victims of HRV is strengthened thorough support provided to national actors in fights against impunity including investigation of violations of human rights, advocacy with authorities and partners to bring the perpetrators of such violations to justice, capacity building of and technical assistance to judicial authorities and provision of legal assistance to victims.
The expected main outcomes are:
1.1    The National Human Rights Institutions (NHRI) are strengthened at central and provincial level delivering more effectively their mandate of protection and promotion of human rights, with special regards to those directly related to the democratic space;      
1.2    NHRI communications and outreach capacities towards the population and the partnership with the government, human rights defenders and CSO and CSO Platforms is more effective;
2.1    Violations of human rights and fundamental freedoms in the context of the civic space are duly monitored and reported and when possible prevented;
2.2    CSOs capacity to engage into monitoring, reporting, promotion of and advocacy for human rights and fundamental freedoms is reinforced;
3.1    Various components of civil society (CSOs, NGOs, media and journalists, and civic activists) effectively play their role in support of knowledge and effective exercise of all human rights and fundamental freedoms by the population;
3.2    States actors fully understand and effectively play their role in promoting and respecting the effective exercise of all human rights and fundamental freedoms (alternative formulation in the results framework: State actors effectively plan their role in protecting the civic space and respecting and promote the effective exercise of human rights and fundamental freedoms by the population);
4.1    HRD, victims and witnesses of HRV are protected from human rights violations and can exercise their rights and freedom without fear.    
5.1     The access to justice and reparation for the victims of HRV is strengthened;
5.2     Impunity is reduced.
The SWPA component does not specifically mention objectives or outcomes in the project proposal, however the reason for the support is stated as: This project funding will enable the United Nations to consolidate the fight against conflict related sexual violence in the DRC. The project will focus on supporting the SWPA's deployment to reinforce the monitoring and analysis of conflict related sexual violence, further engage with parties to the conflict to more effectively prevent CRSV and advocate for the protection of women, girls, boys and men. 
The key priorities of the SWPA are:
1. Monitoring, analysis and reporting;
2. Support for the implementation of FARDC and PNC Action Plans;
3. Strengthening engagement with non-state actors;
4. CRSV mainstreaming.

